    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The Herschel mission has built a view in which filamentary structures are omnipresent in molecular clouds, possibly governing their entire star formation process. In this view, high-mass stars and star-clusters form preferentially in massive filaments whose internal properties differ from those of low-mass ones. What is crucially missing is the knowledge of how massive filaments fragment and collapse to form stars. With ALMA, we will fill this gap by describing the fragmentation of one massive filament in great detail. Most importantly, the observations allow us to establish how the filament fragments connect to protostars in the filament. We will observe the nearest high-mass filament, the Orion filament, in 110 GHz continuum and C18O line emission. Together with our Herschel and LABOCA data, the ALMA data give us the highest-fidelity column density data ever obtained for a molecular cloud. We will determine the fragmentation mode of the filament with a novel technique and constrain its evolutionary scenario. We then employ our unique protostar census, given by the Herschel Orion Protostar Survey, and explain how the small-scale fragments give rise to the protostars in the cloud.</prp:abstract>
